post_text: A senior night for the memory books! Congratulations to our 5 outstanding volleyball seniors as they are excellent teammates on the court along with being positive role models in our school and community. Even though tonight was our first home match of the season, we were able to honor and thank our seniors along with their parents for all the memories they have provided for the Kenmare Honkers Family! The memories made and friendships built will last a lifetime! Good luck the rest of the season Honkers!

We are also hopeful that the plan we created for Kenmare School District will help us to not have to go through what our friends in Trenton are going through. post_text:
Hello Little School (K-2) Families,

After reflecting on the week and getting parent/staff feedback, we decided to have buses pick up in the back of the school and parents pick up in the front. This will prevent us from not being able to see traffic when kids are coming out of the building in the back. Parents, we will now use the FRONT for pick up and drop off. Buses will now drop off and pick up in the back. As always, please be cautious when picking up your children as we have lots of little bodies running out of school excited and not always aware of their surroundings.

Thank you for your patience while we iron out our kinks!

Sincerely,

Mrs. Hennix

post_text:
Effective until further notice, blue passes will no longer be issued except for appointments. Students must bring a parent note to the office that morning stating they have an appointment and the time they are leaving. As of now, we have a closed campus and unfortunately, some have used the blue pass to leave for lunch. Our goal is to provide a safe and healthy environment for our students so that we can continue with face to face instruction. Our hopes are that closing campus is temporary so we are asking your patience with this.
Dr. Godfrey

post_text: Dear Parents, Kenmare School District will be following the Smart Restart visitor procedures tomorrow. That means that except for the parents that were contacted by the school, parents will not be able to accompany their children into the building for drop-off. We ask that any time a parent intends to visit the school, they call ahead, wait at the door to be let in, have their temperature taken, wear a mask, and report to the office. We will bring items or your children to you. If you are bringing your children to school tomorrow, please feel free to accompany them to the door and wish them an amazing first day back. Thank you for your patience and support and we are very excited for your children to return to school.
text: Dear Parents, Kenmare School District will be following the Smart Restart visitor procedures tomorrow. We ask that any time a parent intends to visit the school, they call ahead, wait at the door to be let in, have their temperature taken, wear a mask, and report to the office. We will bring items or your children to you. If you are bringing your children to school tomorrow, please feel free to accompany them to the door and wish them an amazing first day back. Thank you for your patience and support and we are very excited for your children to return to school.

post_text:
Dear Stakeholders,
Tonight during the Special School Board meeting, the School Board appointed Dr. Godfrey as the COVID Coordinator for Kenmare School District. The School Board also voted to change the start day of the school year to August 26th. Staff will report on their regular scheduled day of August 17. This will give us extra time to ensure our Smart Restart plan is complete and communicated in depth to our families. Next week, I will be convening a district task force to begin developing our plan to return to school. While we discussed fairly solid options tonight, we want to make sure what we do moving forward is in the best interest of our students' health, safety, and educational needs while also adhering to the Governor's guidelines. I would also like to ensure all of you that you will be informed every step of the way. Thank you for supporting our district!
Dr. Godfrey

Tonight in Governor Burgum's press conference, he and Superintendent Baesler laid out the requirements and guidance for reopening schools this fall. Two primary responsibilities of our school district will be creating a Health Plan and revising our Distance Learning Plan. I will be meeting with the school board to discuss some options we can implement to maintain social distancing protocol while ensuring the students of Kenmare School District receive an equitable and positive educational experience. Please be patient as we work through the development of these plans and I promise all of you that you will be continually informed as we move forward.
Thank you,
Dr. Godfrey

üéìGRADUATE PARADE REMINDERüéì After the graduation ceremony on June 14, the seniors will be featured in a parade around Kenmare! The vehicles will be decorated by the seniors themselves and the seniors will appear in alphabetical order by last name.

The parade will begin at 3 p.m. from the Kenmare High School parking lot, go down Division Street to the park, head north on 1st Avenue NW, then turn east on 6th Street, and finish by heading south down Central Avenue.

If you can't be at the ceremony, come downtown or stand along the parade route to congratulate and celebrate members of the Class of 2020!

post_text:
üéìGRADUATION UPDATEüéì

Due to the strong possibility of inclement weather on Sunday, graduation ceremonies will be moved to the auditorium. Each student may invite up to eight family members. The auditorium will be sectioned off for families, and seniors will participate in a drawing after graduation practice on Saturday to select their family's spot. No other members of the community will be allowed inside the school during the ceremony. When students are called upon to receive their diplomas, the school board president will place the diploma on a table for the student to retrieve. Parents who wish to, may join their graduate on the stage to physically present the diploma to them. The ceremony will be live streamed on the District's Facebook page and seniors will participate in a car parade afterward.
Dr. Godfrey

post_text:
For anyone confused about the election requirements for absentee voting, I'm including below North Dakota Century Code that addresses school district elections. Dr. Godfrey

NDCC ¬ß 16.1-07-09 permits an absent voter to personally deliver the absente voter‚Äôs ballot to the appropriate officer‚Äôs office (i.e., the school district business manager) at any time before 5 p.m. on the day before the election. Drop boxes are an alternative or supplement to personal delivery to the business manager‚Äôs office during school building closures due to the COVID-19 pandemic. All drop boxes should be removed and their use discontinued at 5 p.m. on the day before the election in order to comply with this requirement. No absentee ballots should be accepted via personal delivery or drop box after 5 p.m. on the day before the election.

üöåSCHOOL MATERIALS PICK-UPüöåWith the school year coming to a close, it's time to collect any borrowed materials from the school so they can be picked up. Please gather any textbooks, materials, AND your Chromebook and charger to be turned in. Pick-ups will start on TUESDAY, MAY 19TH for those who have been receiving school lunch during the school closure. Pick-ups for everyone else will be WEDNESDAY, MAY 20TH.

Our bus drivers have many places to get to, so please have your materials ready to give to them when they stop at your house. If there are any questions, please contact an administrator.

üéìGRADUATE PARADEüéì After the graduation ceremony on June 14, the seniors will be featured in a parade around Kenmare! The vehicles will be decorated by the seniors themselves and the seniors will appear in alphabetical order by last name.

The parade will begin at 3 p.m. from the Kenmare High School parking lot, go down Division Street to the park, head north on 1st Avenue NW, then turn east on 6th Street, and finish by heading south down Central Avenue.

If you can't be at the ceremony, come downtown or stand along the parade route to congratulate and celebrate members of the Class of 2020!

SCHOOL BOARD ELECTION: A school board election vote will be held on JUNE 9TH, 2020. Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, this will be an ABSENTEE BALLOT ONLY election.

You can vote in one of two ways:
1. USPS mail
2. Drop off at one of the secure voting locations: Front door of the KHS building, or Kenmare City Hall.

You can obtain an absentee ballot application by going to our website, going to https://vip.sos.nd.gov/absentee, or contacting business manager Mary Ann Melin. For more information, click this link! https://www.kenmare.k12.nd.us/o/kenmare-school-district-28/page/school-board-election-2020

shared_text:
ND Department of Public Instruction
April 23 at 4:48 PM ¬∑

At his daily news conference on Thursday, April 23, Gov. Burgum was asked his reaction to the state of Minnesota's decision to keep school buildings closed for the remainder of the 2019-20 school year. He said he had "no reaction" to the Minnesota decision and said he was "not leaning in one direction or the other" on the question of whether in-person instruction in North Dakota's schools will resume during the current academic year. "We've got to make decisions here based on our own data."

The music trip is canceled for this school year.
For those parents who have paid any money for the music trip, you will be awarded a full refund, less the $100 non-refundable deposit. You must make arrangements for the cancellation by April 6th. Please contact Music Travel Consultants at 317-637-0837 to begin processing your refund. You may also contact Mike Gray, director of sales, at Michael.gray@musictravel.com.
Dr. Godfrey

DISTANCE LEARNING INFORMATION: KPS is going digital! In order to abide by Governor Burgum's guidelines, we are setting up digital learning for students. Teachers will be sending information to students through your KPS email or through Remind and Facebook for younger grades.

We've added a new tab to our website (www.kenmare.k12.nd.us) titled "Distance Learning." This tab has tutorials for Zoom and Google Classroom, guides to resources and a document titled "Opportunities for Learning" where all teacher links are housed. Please refer back to this tab on the website (pictured below) because it will continue to be updated as more information is shared.

Again, be sure to fill out the Nutritional Needs Survey if you are in need of meals at this time and contact Dr. Godfrey if you are in need of internet services.

Please do not hesitate to reach out if you have questions--we can get through this new adventure together!

I received this message today and encourage all of your (especially this year's seniors) to contact her and give your input. Dr. Godfrey

Hi. The Minot Daily News is interested in doing stories for its upcoming Progress edition on how coronavirus and school closures are affecting this year's graduating class of seniors. We are also interested in talking to administrators, teachers and to parents about how they and students are managing or will be managing alternative methods of education at home. Would it be possible for you to pass my phone number and email along to teachers and students and ask them to contact me by phone or email? I hope to do this story for an edition that will run the first week in April and to talk to some area students and teachers yet this week. I can be reached at 701-857-1945 or by email at ajohnson@minotdailynews.com Thanks. Andrea Johnson, Minot Daily News

PARENT/STUDENT PICK-UP REMINDER: Parents and students are allowed to pick up materials/devices on TUESDAY, March 24th from 10:00 am to 12:00 pm and 1:00 pm to 3:00 pm for the high school building, and 1:00 pm to 3:00 pm for the K-2 building. Students in grades 3-6 will check out a Chromebook to take home for E-Learning. Students in grades 7-12 already have Chromebooks checked out in their name. Students in grades K-2 will be allowed to check out a Chromebook IF there is not a device for them to use at home.

Students and parents will not be allowed in the building for your safety--those materials will be brought out to you. Please remember to practice social distancing while waiting. KPS wants you to stay healthy and safe!

If there any questions, please send a message to the Facebook page or an email to tgodfrey@mykps.us or tcunningham@mykps.us

Students, we miss you and hope you are healthy and safe! üíõ

post_text:
Dear Parents,
As many of you know, Governor Burgum has announced statewide school closures for one week beginning tomorrow due to the COVID-19 pandemic. The administrative team will be meeting tomorrow to develop an emergency action plan, to put into place, should school closures continue past next week. If for some reason your children rely on school lunch to meet their nutritional needs, please email me. We will make sure that lunches are provided for them. I am pledging to you that we will protect our children from harm and ensure their academic needs are provided for. I ask that you be vigilant and patient. Your children are our first and most important priority. My cell phone number is 907-317-2289 if you feel the need to contact me at anytime.
Dr. Godfrey

If for some reason your children rely on school lunch to meet their nutritional needs, please email me. We will make sure that lunches are provided for them. I am pledging to you that we will protect our children from harm and ensure their academic needs are provided for. I ask that you be vigilant and patient. Your children are our first and most important priority. My cell phone number is 907-317-2289 if you feel the need to contact me at anytime.
Dr. Godfrey

CENSUS 2020: On April 1, 2020, the United States will conduct a census to determine the current population of the United States. The census count will be used to determine ‚Äì among other things ‚Äì how seats within the U.S. House of Representatives are divided among states and how federal funds are dispersed to each state. These funds are used for Medicaid, Free and Reduced Lunch programs, educational grants, Disabled Veterans Outreach Programs, social services, and rural funding for first responders. Help our state receive the funding we deserve!

See https://www.nd.gov/news-events/census-2020 for more information.

The Kenmare Speech team hit the open road Saturday morning for Minot to compete in the Nedrose Cardinal Invitational meet along with about 30 other schools. Our students all gave a great effort and came home with the following awards:
Jaden McNeiley - 1st in Storytelling (State Qualifying) and 2nd in Radio broadcasting
Madison Griffin - 4th in Poetry
Megan Zimmer and Isabel Sieg - 4th in Humorous Duo
Arand Bartlett - 5th in Extemp Speaking and 8th in Impromptu
Isabel Sieg - 7th in Extemp Programmed Reading
Abbey Kohler - Top Novice in Serious Prose
Jesse Rodin - Top Novice in Speech to Entertain

post_text:
Dear Parents,
Recently, we discovered several incidents of cyber bullying between students at Kenmare Public Schools. This can be considered a violation of the school district's nondiscrimination and anti-harassment policy. A violation of the policy can happen even when these types of behavior occur outside of school and affect students while they are at school. We intend to be proactive with this issue. I am in the process of finding guest speakers to educate our students on the damage cyber bullying can cause. When those educational sessions are scheduled, I will be notifying parents and asking you to join us as well. Please be vigilant at home and convey to your children that cyber bullying is bullying. It's mean, malicious, and hurtful. We will work together with you to make sure cyber bullying does not become the norm for our kids. Thank you for your support and for entrusting us with your children's safety.
Dr. Godfrey

post_text:
Kenmare School District would like to help support Minot Civil Air Patrol in their efforts with Wreaths Across America. Each year, CAP units in North Dakota place wreaths on the graves of military veterans as a display of honor and respect. Each wreath costs $15 and Minot CAP received $5 in return to help supply cadets with uniforms and essential resources for their program. If you are unfamiliar with Civil Air Patrol, please visit the following link to find out more http://www.ndcap.us. If you are interested in helping sponsor Minot CAP with financial donations, you can send those donations to the high school office and we will ensure they are distributed to the Minot CAP appropriately. Please make any checks payable to Kenmare School District and we bring all collected donations to them by their March meeting.
Dr. Godfrey
